			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2024</a> paper:</span><br><i>Cloud Programming Languages and Infrastructure from Code: An Empirical Study</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/GeorgSimhandl.html">Georg Simhandl</a>, <a href="../profile/UweZdun.html">Uwe Zdun</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3687997.3695643">10.1145/3687997.3695643</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagM">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> The paper is primarily an empirical study assessing productivity/efficacy of infrastructure-from-code approaches.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> It evaluates usability for (novice) developers and developer-experience implications of different approaches.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2d.html"><span class="tagL">T2D: Deployment</span></a><ul><li> The subject matter is cloud deployment and provisioning, comparing language vs SDK approaches to infrastructure.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3f.html"><span class="tagL">T3F: API</span></a><ul><li> Infrastructure-from-code solutions are positioned as SDK/APIs that abstract cloud resources programmatically.
</li></ul></li></ul>
